[[File:Tunisia Antica.jpg|thumb|right|Map showing town in [[Roman North Africa]].]]'''Sidi Ahmed Djedidi''' is a town and hill near [[Hammamet, Tunisia]], 64 [[Kilometer]]s [[south]] of [[Tunis]]. It is located at 36.4[[North|n]] and 10.4[[east|e]].

During the [[Roman Empire]] the [[town]] was known as [[Elephantaria]] and was a [[civitas]] of the [[Roman North Africa|Africa Proconsularis]].<ref>[http://www.gcatholic.org/diocese/former/to693.htm   Elephantaria] at GCatholic.org.</ref><ref>[http://www.travelingluck.com/africa/Tunisia/Nābul/_2465642_sidi+Jedidi.html  Sidi Ahmed Djedidi].</ref> The city at that time was the [[cathedra|seat]] of an ancient [[Christian]] [[Bishopric]], which survives today as a[[Titular see]] of the [[Roman Catholic Church]].<ref>[[Annuario Pontificio]] 2013 (Libreria Editrice Vaticana 2013 {{ISBN|978-88-209-9070-1}}).</ref>

